deck_name: THE ULTIMATE DECK (Devine Beasts, Exodia, Evil Eye...)
deck_excerpt: Devine Beasts, Evil Eye, Exodia, performapal Sky Magician, Blue Eyes White Dragon etc.
deck_description: I dont own all of the cards, but I just wanted to create a deck with all those super strong and rare cards. So I did. I know its not perfect. I should have also used right and left hand of the magician. But idc. I just wanted to make a cool deck.
This is my first deck sumbitted just use and learn it

First of all I'll note I'm only recently returned to Yu-Gi-Oh! so bear with me if I miss a few things.

This is a going second deck primarily. It has tools to help going first but it's best going second.

Your main win condition here is obviously Gren Maju Da Eiza for the OTK. Easiest possible way is using Eater of Millions to banish your extra deck giving Gren Maju 6000 ATK on its own.

Gizmek helps with this while providing an annoying board presence even on your opponent's turn. It also is your target for the effects of Armageddon Knight and Dark Grepher unless you have Dimensional Fissure or Macro Cosmos active in which case their target becomes Necroface or in a pinch Snipe Hunter.

Speaking of, Snipe Hunter is there to hopefully draw out your opponent's counter plays. However if he doesn't (and in some cases won't because your opponent is waiting for a more powerful effect to negate) you can do some pretty effective damage to their board while also using the Dangers to mess with them. Keep in mind Dangers still work if banished when discarded.

Speaking of the Dangers, this deck includes a Level 8 XYZ package as a potential backup. This just helps with consistency but also can help with taking out pieces of your opponent's board especially if you have a Gren Maju and/or Eater in your hand that you'd rather not have negated.

This deck is definitely rogue and definitely anti-meta. It will brick occasionally and it will get beat by efficient combos and if you really don't care about that you will love it. Personally I just adore this deck because opponents will rarely if ever be prepared for it unless they're running a broken combo like Avian in which case you'd be in trouble no matter what.
This is optimized to fight against an evileye deck.
Things are starting to look up a little bit. The collection still needs some help

deck_name: Progression Draft - Poorman's Clown Control (Metal Raiders)
deck_excerpt: First attempts on a control deck with minor offensive options
deck_description:
Another week, another deck. It really is something to pull a new set that basically makes most of the old cards seem useless by comparison.

Despite the ominous introduction, I haven't changed much in my strategy from before. The only thing that improved from last week was the offensive part (every tribute got its well-deserved retirement and non-tribute powerhouses like Jirai Gumo, Seven-Colored Fish und Ryu-Kishin Powered entered the fray) in conjunction with a few nice control tools in Paralyzing Potion and the Clowns.

The biggest impact had the staples: I won't pretend that dual Dark Hole + dual Mirror Force didn't carry the heck out of me. I unfortunately didn't get Imperial Order, Magician of Faith or Solemn Judgment; the first pretty much is universally owned by everyone except me!

But yeah, I managed. I successfully defended the crown against my friends.

The concept of the deck is the same as the last: Sit on 2k defenders, summon your tribute guy and dominate. Sanga of the Thunder und Suijin replaced my old tribute payoffs and definitely pulled their weight.

The other big portion of the deck was, again, Yami. This time, the boost was much more significant than before: Mystical Elf, her cuter sister and Aqua Madoor could survive any encounter with Jirai Gumo under Yami. Ryu-Kishin Powered could at least trade with the strongest beater without any drawbacks, Seven-Colored Fish. Crass Clown could also stand its own against former non-tribute stars Uraby and Skull Red bird, but that barely ever came up.

The other monsters were mostly just filler that made sense given the feel of the deck: Giant Soldier of Stone and Prevent Rat are just solid normals since 2k defenders are the heart and soul of this deck.  Pulling thre Prevent Rat also allowed me to kick Spirit of the Harp in the site who had negative synergy with Yami.

Hane-Hane still punishes opposing tribute payoffs and equip-heavy setups.

The clowns were decent with protection (Paralyzing Potion or Swords) but were kind of meh in this stage of the game. Dream Clown nicely punished walling up, though, and occasionally forced stronger 2k defenders like Giant Soldier of Stone and Aqua Madoor into attack!

Masked Sorcerer is sort of a win more card and intended as such. I lack any form of search or draw power since I didn't pull any of the big searchers or Pot of Greed, so I looked for a way to get through my deck faster. It made good situations better and snowballed somewhat easier with Stim-Pack, but nothing more.

Stop Defense, Fissure, Dark Hole and Tribute to the Doomed are all meant to keep opposing field building in check and disrupt potential counter-walling up. Block Attack served a similar purpose as the "reverse walls" of Dark Elf and Jirai Gumo have poor Def.

The secret stars were the equips, however. Paralyzing Potion nicely vegetablized any threatening monster on the opposing end and slowed the game down enough for me to either build up advantage or remove the card with the clowns. Stim-Pack was amazing: It provided huge momentum swings and turned any of my decent attacking monsters into virtual powerhouses. The drawback only hurt me once. Usually, your monsters won't sit around so long to make the attack loss actually noticeable. And if you do, you're usually in a stalemate situation already. Thankfully, most of my friends missed this amazing card!

Mirror Force is just Mirror Force and really enabled the clowns. You could nicely dismantle set cards with a position change and be protected by the holy barrier against offensive threats.

The Extra is just filler cards, ranked according to looks.

The side is, for the most part, filler stuff. Sword & Shield seemed cool as a finisher on paper but I ultimately never used it. Plain walling up was usually more beneficial than a big offensive push.

Tremendous Fire was doing too little for field presence to ever warrant a main slot.

Time Wizard was supposed to serve as a third, riskier Dark Hole. Sided it in once but never used the effect.

Two-Pronged is still a decent tribute spot removal but thanks to my generally better tools available now, I never really bothered with it.

Remove Trap was pretty much dead since there are no permanent traps to speak of where it would work. Imperial Order as the only notable one for my deck negates it >.<

Mask of Darkness was supposed to recycle Mirror Forces. Never put it in once, though. I valued my other control tools too much to justify a wonky two-card combo in an already somewhat inconsistent deck.

deck_excerpt: Use Tribrigades and Bujins to make spicy Link plays
deck_description: Hello everyone! Sorry for my long 6 month hiatus. College, the pandemic, and things in my personal life forced me to take a break from the game for a long while. This list is an updated version of my Bujin Tri-Brigade list from October 2020. In 6 months, a whole LOT has changed! The first thing that inspired me to recreate this list is the fact that Bujin will be receiving some new support in the next set. I was taken aback by Konami's decision to breathe life back into a dead strategy, but I'm not complaining. Here's a brief summary of the new cards! Bujin Torfiune: Fun fact: This is the only Bujin Main Deck monster that is based on another Monster card rather than a character from GX. Anyway, you can Tribute this guy toSpecial Summon 2 Bujin monsters with different Types from your deck and when you Xyz Summon a Bujin Xyz Monster while Torifune is in the GY, you can equip him to the Xyz Monster which makes it banish anything it destroys by battle. This makes Susanowo finally worth going into and promotes a more aggressive strategy with the archetype rather than a control strategy. Bujin Mahitotsu YUGI BOY! (sorry) This guy can be Special Summoned by discarding another Bujin monster (great for getting Bujingi monsters out of your hand.) You then have two effects you can chose from; you can either send a Bujin monster from your hand to add another from your deck or banish a Bujin monster to send a Bujin monster from your deck. This is vulnerable to Ash but you can still get rid of Bujin monsters you don't want in your hand and in this deck you can set up Tri-Brigade Revolt by banishing Bujin monsters. Bujintersection Sadly, this is not an archetype exclusive Kaiser Colloseum. Instead, it protects your Bujins from being destroyed by card effects (except in the Battle Phase.) You can also send a Bujin from your field to the yard to negate the effect of a face-up card, and you can destroy Bujintersection during the End Phase to Special Summon any Bujin monster you want from your Graveyard. The rest of the deck is a fairly standard affair, just do Tribrigade plays and make Bujin Xyz Monsters. Any feedback is always welcome. Stay gold! :)

deck_excerpt: Harpie deck pure version adding just Kerass and Apex Avian. Well control and fun matches. JUST SEE IT!!!
deck_description:
Hi! We are TRYNDAWARRIOR93 and we are new Yugioh Youtuber.

On this link https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2kJS_S3LFUM you can see our video explaining all about this deck .

We know harpie could be mixed with tribrigade, but we only use Kerass on this version.

Our deck is focus on have control with Apex + Statue + Harpie´s Feather Storm.

In addition, if you´re wallet let it xD you can use x3 Impermanence changing it for Blossom and Effect Veiler.

Blackwing deck, that can normally end with 1 lv4 xyz and a Infinity(basic combo) or more(for people who thinks more than me).
  • Combo Starters: 1 - Any Blackwing: They can Special Summon themselves, summon Wise Strix and start combo. PS: Hand full of spells/ Only 1 Summonable card = Brick.
  • Basic Combos: 1 - Any 2 Blackwings monsters: Special both of them -> Link Summon Wise Strix -> Use effect to summon Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite from your deck -> Link Summon The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche -> Use effect to mill The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots from your deck, set The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine(If you have no traps in your GY) or Phantom Knights' Fog Blade(If you have traps in GY) -> Use the effect of Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite in your GY; return The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche -> Activate The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine(since you have no traps in your gy) -> Xyz Summon using Zephyros and the Trap(The Xyz can be your choice, I normally summon dweller). 2 - 3  monsters or more that can be Summoned(Including 2 Harmattan the Dust or 1 Lv4 Blackwing): NS first Blackwing -> Special Summon other 2 cards(If you have 2 Harmattan the Dust, NS first copy, then add the level to the second, so you have a Lv4 Monster) -> Link Summon Wise Strix, leaving at least 1 Lv4 card in the field -> Activate Wise Strix effect, Special Summon Zephros the Elite -> Xyz Summon into Raidraptor - Force Strix -> Activate Force Strix effect, detach Zephros the Elite, add Raidraptor - Strangle Lanius or Raider's Wing -> Activate Wise Strix effect, set Rank-Up-Magic Soul Shave Force from your Deck -> If you added Raider's Wing: Use it's effect; detach from Force Strix, Special Summon it -> Link Summon into Bardiche, using Xyz and Link -> Activate Bardiche's effect, mill Silent Boots; Set Shade Brigantine from your Deck -> Activate Shade Brigantine -> Xyz Summon using Raider's Wind and Shade Brigantine(Your choice) -> Activate Soul Shave Force -> Rank-Up Force Strix into Cyber Dragon Infinity -> If you added Raidraptor - Strangle Lanius: Link Summon Bardiche using Xyz and Link -> Activate Soul Shave Force -> Rank-Up Force Strix into Cyber Dragon Infinity -> Activate Bardiche's effect, mill Silent Boots; set Shade Brigantine -> Activate Strange Lanius from your hand -> Xyz Summon using Strange Lanius and Shade Brigantine(Your choice, but only DARK monsters can be summoned now).
  • Cons: 1 - Any handtrap: At the start of the combo, if your opponent negates Wise Strix, you're dead... There is nothing you can do, unless you have other monsters, to link into Bardiche. 2 - Not a comeback: Same case as number 1, this is a total non-meta combo... Any negate can break this easily. 3 - Tag Duels: You can play it if you're 1st, otherwise there is nothing you can do... If you're 3rd/4th there is probably negates, which you can't handle and if your partner doesn't have a counter for it... You're both dead.
  • Pros: 1 - Versatibility: You can probably combo more than I've shown and I didn't say anything about Simoon the Poison Wind as a combo starter. I've only shown the basic so you can continue it. 2 - Bricks: There is a lot of monsters on it, many of them can Special itself from the hand. It's very hard to brick with this deck. And you can even Pot of Disparity the Synchros, if needed.
  • Side: I haven't put anything on side, because I'm bad at the Side Deck. This deck probably can't use Handtraps, because it would probably be a brick, unless you start using Deskbots/Mecha Phantom, but that is too much for a deck.
Good luck at using this deck and thanks for clicking on this page.

deck_excerpt: If your opponent makes a special summon(s) you basically win the duel.
deck_description: This Deck is one of those rare cases where we have a card that somehow compares to Maxx "C", but the card is not abused, not even used.- This is the Case of Naturia Antjaw Naturia Antjaw a card that has no restriction, not even limitation since it does not even have an effect once per turn. Naturia Antjaw Effect: (Each time the opponent makes a special summon, special summon any naturia level 3 or lower from the deck.) (up to the same Antjaw) It has good targets like: Naturia Sunflower (Negate activation of monster effects). Naturia Rosewhip (Limits opponent to only use one s/t per turn). Naturia Stinkbug (Protect all your naturia monsters from the Battle phase). Naturia Marron (It's the draw engine of the deck) All this plus powerful "generic" cards allows us to have a "fairly consistent" deck since a simple foolish burial gods allows us to play. This deck have quite a few starters like: Foolish burial Gods (send Naturia sacred tree from the deck to the gy to search antjaw from the deck to the hand. (Basically one card combo) Magician's Souls:(It allows the deck to reach Antjaw without even using the normal summon.) You send Palladium Oracle Mana as a cost to summon Magician's Souls . You can send up to 2 Naturia sacred tree from your hand to the gy with magician's souls which becomes a +2 (send 2 to draw 2 and search 2). It also allows us to protect Antjaw by battle since with him we can make linkuriboh, so the opponent cannot make normal summon pass battle phase and destroy antjaw to play during the MP2. Level 6 monsters and the new retort fusion: Basically Beatrice Lady of the eternal is to search Antjaw and Marron quickly.   This deck has the same broken extenders as Antjaw like: Worm bait: 2 free tokens for link and synchro plays. Hop Ear Squadron: Make Herald of the arc light during the opponent turn. It's a pretty casual deck, but fun uwu.

deck_excerpt: I feel like playing Stigmatika with something other than Despia would be miles better
deck_description: This deck is meant to bring out a ton of fusions turn 1 which have really no interactions on your opponent's turn so you are better off going second to otk. Most of the Stigmatika cards in LIOV do not work that well with the Stigmatika/Despia support in DAMA especially since the Despia are Fairies and not dragons and they are also not Light Attribute. Hecatrice and Vahalla ar my interpretation of how to get to a Light monster easier, but the baby chaos dragons along with Chaos Space might work better if you want to utilize Stigmatika of White. 3 Ash, 3 Albus, 3 Hecatrice are your non-Despia mons. Dramaturgia of Despia is a very lackluster negate, but it summons itself if its banished from FIELD or HAND by something like Albion which makes it only a one-of. Albert is your most important Normal/Special Summon aside from Albus as he searches a Stigmatika Spell/Trap which will often be Theatre as it has a fusion effect that isn't limited to using a dragon monster as one of the materials. Despian of Tragedy is probably your best form of consistency as it searches a Despia upon being banished or sent for a fusion or other effect. Its second effect gets you back Curtain Rise but "only 1 effect per turn, and only once that turn." Despian of Comedy is aight but you should probably side it if you believe in there being targeting effects when the game is more about negates. 3 Valhalla. 3 Fusion Deployment for Albus. 3 Despia, Stigmatika Theatre whose fusion eff doesnt 't restrict you to using a dragon as material. 3 Stigmatika Curtain Rise which is bonkers as it either searches, summons from deck, and it protects against board wipes. 1 Stigmatika of White since Despia are Faries. 3 Prosperity. 3 Retort Fusion which is ironic due to Instant Fusion. 3 Super Poly. 1 Dogmatika Encounter which gives you access to Albus I guess. ED: 1 The First Darklord which is a Punishment target and it gets you a Fairy every turn. 1 Dracrown of Mysterion which is just funny I guess since I have like a seizure trying to understand its effect with my ape brain. 1 Despian Proscenium which is like Goyo Emperor (?) and Evil HERO Inferno Wing (?). 2 Despain Quaeritis which is the easiest fusion to summon, otk potential, it floats into Albus. 2 Albion which is one of my favourite cards since it has so much versatility. 2 Titaniklad which is here for the atk gain and EP Albus search. 1 Brigand which is an Albus/Albion target. Starving Venom for Super Poly. 2 Musician King as a Light off of Retort Fusion. 2 N'tss to send off of Punishment. Side Deck is nothing special. deck_excerpt: FYI, these are cards I actually own. I'm aware Evolzar Dolkka and Animadorned Archosaur are extremely useful in this deck, but I haven't either. Plus,
deck_description:
With the banning of True King of All Calamities, the boss of this deck has shifted to Ultimate Conductor Tyranno, though it isn't the only way to win. For pesky cards difficult to get rid of, such as Red Eyes Dark Dragoon, Dogoran, the Mad Flame Kaiju, can easily take it's place and get flipped face down with UCT's ability. Gizmek Kaku is useful against opponents' big Link monsters, such as an opposing Borrelsword Dragon, so long as it remains in the Extra Deck Zone. With all the banishing done for UCT and Miscellaneousaurus, summoning Overtex Qoatlu and bolstering Tyranno Infinity's attack should be a cakewalk. Plus, with the pairing of Overtex Qoaltus and Lost World, you can easily pop off Babycerasaurus's and Petiterandon's effects from the deck. True King Lithosagym is great for preventing any possiblilty of annoying Extra Deck monsters, such as Dragoon. True King Agnimazud effortlessly gets around the effects that prevent card destruction, as it banishes.

In regards to the extra deck, Evolzar Laggia is great for stopping the activation of card effects or summoning of monsters. Additionally, after his effect pops off, summoning an Ultimate Conductor Tyranno should be simple as pie (or is it pi? I honestly haven't a clue). Dark Rebellion and Dark Requiem both do essentially the same thing, though Requiem's effect is much more potent and cheaper to activate. Knightmare Phoenix is useful as spell destruction and sending dinosaur monsters to the grave for an UCT. Borrelsword Dragon is useful to pair up with UCT since it can change a monster to defense position on either players' turns. Martial Metal Marcher, Goyo Guardian, Infernity Doom Archfiend, and Virtual World Beast - Jiujiu are mainly there to help get out Crystal Wing and Clear Wing, though they are useful in other ways. Jiujiu will almost always be protected by its own effect in this deck as monsters are frequently hitting the grave. Its additional effect also serves to bolster Tyranno Infinity and/or summon Overtex Qoaltus. It's easy to clear your hand with this deck, allowing Infernity Doom Archfiend's effects to have full potency. Finally, Goyo Guardian serves to prevent some cards from hitting the opponent's graveyard if they rely on it while bolstering your own defenses.

deck_excerpt: Unbreakable Numeron Deck 2021. Go easly for OTK combo and overkill your opponent or Summon Big Boys Numeronius Monsters C1000 / iC1000 with 100000 att
deck_description:
Hello guys, Here is the new version of Numeron deck that I built. I've worked a lot on this deck and I succeed to defeat a lot of meta decks with this deck. I hope you will enjoy it. With this deck, you have 92% to draw Numeron Network on your first turn if you start second and 86% if you play first. There is two possibilities with this deck : I/ Going for OTK combo I've played a lot Numeron decks and I know that most of the time we quickly win by OTK our opponent during our first turns by summon all Numeron monsters and attacking with them (first one : 1000 attack -> 2000 attack -> 4000 attack -> 8000 attack !)... In order to do that, I added these cards on this deck :
  • Against monsters :
    • Forbidden Droplet : just wow with Numeron decks, because it doesn't target, it can negate multiple monsters effects and your opponent cannot respond to its effect. This card can also negate "surprise" monster effects during the battle phase, which is very welcome.
    • Lightning Storm : amazing card, especially for Numeron decks
    • And the final one... Lava Golem... Which is just the most AMAZING card for Numeron decks. You can tribute two monsters on the opponent side to summon this card on your opponent side. This card is just perfect against most of "full board ultimate 7 negates....". Also I added Dark Spirit's Mastery in order to search this card. Because after a lot of games, I realized how good is this card with Numeron decks and most of the time, I win by the help of this card.
  • Against "Full trap board trololo go fu*** yourself", I added:
    • You can use Lightning Storm, which can also be used against monsters
    • Red reboot : this card is done for OTK decks. So it's just a mandatory to have this card on Numeron decks.
    • Harpie's Feather Duster
    • Hey, Trunade : I discovered this card recently... And wow, it's a greater "Red reboot" which is not limited. Hey hey !! Perfect.
  II/ Summoning the Big Numeronius Boys The alternative is to try to summon Numeronius cards : Number C1000: Numeronius or Number iC1000: Numeronius Numeronia. This combo is not recommanded if you want to play safe and just win... But against bad players, you can have a lot of fun playing this combo. You have Unchained monsters to do that. The combo in order to do that :
  1. You need in your hand : 1 or 2 Numeron Network (92% to draw 1 Numeron Network on your first turn) and one Unchained monster.
    1. If you just have 1 Numeron Network, you will need to have another one on your next turn in order to do this combo... Which is not very recommanded because you just count on the luck.
  2. Summon the four Numeron monsters
  3. Summon Number C1 Numeron Chaos Gate Sunya. Which will banish all monsters on the field
  4. Protect yourself by using One Day of Peace or an Unchained monster in defense mode or Numeron Wall
  5. End your turn
  6. If you survived and you still have Numeron Network on your field, summon Number C1 Numeron Chaos Gate Sunya which was banished
  7. Then use an Unchained monster from your hand to destroy your Number C1 Numeron Chaos Gate Sunya
  8. Use :
    1. The effect of Numeron Network to use the effect of Numeron Chaos Ritual from your deck
    2. Or use directly the effect of Numeron Chaos Ritual from your hand, if this card is in your hand.
  9. Then summon Number C1000: Numeronius... Which has 10000 attack.
  10. Then, if you are lucky and your opponent destroy by card effect Number C1000: Numeronius, you will have the possibility to summon Number iC1000: Numeronius Numeronia with 100000 attack :D ... It's not the best card it's true, but I love this card, it's very sexy to succeed to summon a 100000 attack monster like this one. And I won some games with this card, so satisfying.
  Tips :
  • If you play first: go direcly to Infinitrack Fortress MegaClops to protect yourself. After that, you can use Forbidden Droplet on Megaclops to destroy it and in order to have the possibility to summon your Numeron monsters. You can also replace MegaClops by Mekk-knight Crusadia Avramax, Borreload Dragon or Apollousa, bow of the goddess
  • If you play against "trololo you can't attack me because I'm a Exodia Player with a lot of cards to prevent attacks", go to Burn effect with Number C1 Numeron Chaos Gate Sunya.
  Have fun, Best regards, Cyncop

deck_excerpt: The deck you see on YouTube! This is our super fun casual Red-Eyes deck that we love playing and playing against! It can hit people for 10k plus, and
deck_description:
Hello, this is the deck we use on our YouTube videos!

We like to do casual Yugioh matches on youtube!

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cQPvrZvYXuI&list=PLN7bNHPmGnd4B8RYlqbp8sVWu-D38tuR6

I dont like to run 3 Red-eyes Insight because it makes the games a bit too same-y, it's an incredible card though!

What cool stuff does this deck do?
1) Can put a Red-Eyes Black Dragon sword on a Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon  t1! That's a massive creature that resurrects normal monsters, cant be killed by effects, and pings you enemy for 500 whenever they do anything!
2) Red-Eyes Fusion out a Meteor Black Comet Dragon or Slash Dragon
3)Suicide Alternative Dragons to bring back to life Red-Eyes Black Dragon's with 4800 Attack!
4) Mirror Force

When I built this a lot of the cards where dirt cheap, I paid 25 cents each for my alternative dragons, and like a buck for the Return of the Dragon lords...It's a shame that this deck has gotten spendy.

I dont like the Red-eyes resurrection traps, I think they are very bad for red-eyes. Monster reborn and Return of Dragonlords lets you resurrect things the turn you need it, and extends your plays greatly. And Return of the Dragonlord's GY effect is insane, especially in a deck that likes to go HUGE with Red-Eyes black dragon sword. The Red-eyes resurrections are more bricks then help

We spent a long time getting this deck to a strong but casual power level we think makes yugioh awesome. As a rule of thumb, we don't like to run Hand Traps like Impermanence/Ash and counter monsters(Like Dragoon, Harbinger, toadally awesome, ect ect) as it allows one to create truly unbeatable boards t1 or set up 1hitKills, and that's just unfun IMO.

Why no Dragoon? I tried running a proxy Dragoon against Stephnie once, and I summoned it, killed both of her Blue eyes White dragons, dealt 6k to her with her own destroyed monsters, and just attacked for game because he couldn't even be hit by her traps. It's a very unfun card that only should be used vrs the meta IMO.

If you have friends that play casual, I cant recommend this deck enough, it's fun and INCREDIBLY consistent!

deck_description:
I'm a returning player. I stopped around the time when Links came in 2017 and have recently returned playing. I've always played Gladiator Beasts and this is my take on them, obviously with a lot of looking around for ideas. Any suggestions are welcomed. I call this deck Gladiator Beast Rejection not because of Gladiator Rejection, but because my focus is to get the big monsters to negate effects, spells, and traps. The objective is to build an unstoppable negate field with Gladiator Beast Domitianus, Gladiator Beast Heraklinos and/or Simorgh, Bird of Sovereignty with Mist Valley Apex Avian. One of my favorite combos is:
  1. Rescue Rabbit with Gladiator Beast Andal (or Gladiator Proving Ground) or Unexpected Dai in hand
    1. If Unexpected Dai, then special summon Gladiator Beast Andal first
  2. Summon Rescue Rabbit and active her effect hoping not to get Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring
  3. Get the two Gladiator Beast Andals
  4. Use one to get Link Spider and summon the third Gladiator Beast Andal from your hand
  5. Go to Test Panther with Link Spider and Gladiator Beast Andal, get Gladiator Beast's Comeback if you don't have it in your hand, otherwise Gladiator Beast Noxious or Gladiator Beast Vespasius or Gladiator Beast Attorix (to make her level 5+)
  6. Activate the effect of Test Panther and get Gladiator Beast Augustus instead of Gladiator Beast Andal, special summon Gladiator Beast Noxious/Gladiator Beast Vespasius/Gladiator Beast Attorix
    1. If Noxious, then throw Gladiator Beast Bestiari or Gladiator Beast Equeste to the grave
    2. In my scenario, I would get Gladiator Beast Noxious
  7. Get Gladiator Beast Tamer Editor out and then special summon Gladiator Beast Domitianus
  8. Link summon Cross-Sheep with Gladiator Beast Tamer Editor and Test Panther
  9. Use the Gladiator Beast's Comeback that you got through Test Panther to summon Gladiator Beast Tamer Editor back from the grave
  10. Special Summon it to a monster zone which Cross-Sheep points to, special summon the level 4 Winged-Beast GB you threw with Gladiator Beast Noxious
  11. Activate the effect of Gladiator Beast Tamer Editor to get Gladiator Beast Heraklinos
  12. Using Cross-Sheep and the level 4 Winged Beast you got through him, go to Simorgh, Bird of Sovereignty
  13. End your turn or attack
  14. Activate the effect of Simorgh, Bird of Sovereignty to get Mist Valley Apex Avian
Now you have on the field:
  1. Gladiator Beast Tamer Editor
  2. Gladiator Beast Domitianus
  3. Gladiator Beast Heraklinos
  4. Simorgh, Bird of Sovereignty
  5. Mist Valley Apex Avian
To me, that's a pretty good field and if there are no negates to this process, the most sensible thing one can do is surrender. There are many more combos. Any comments and feedback are welcome. :) Some obvious cards that are not in the deck because I don't have them:
  • Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring
  • Harpie's Feather Duster
  • Infinite Impermanence
  • Evenly Matched

My take so far on the new deck.

Any suggestions are appreciated.

So, I saw this archetype and i fucking love it. It  has a really cool goth aesthethic and i'm very m e n t a l l y i l l rn (more so than normal) so im fucking vibin with this archetype. Anyway here's a deck guide because I like these. This will prob be really obselete soon when more cards get revealed but whatever it's fucking cool. Tips appreciated because idk what i'm d- GOD DAMMIT EPSTIEN, I FUCKING TOLD YOU TH ERULES. YOU STAY IN THE GOD DAMN BASEMENT WHEN GUESTS ARE OVER

3x Tragedy- Tragedy is a great card, as it's basically a ROTA for the archetype once it's sent to the grave. This is an archetype designed with ditching cards to the grave in mind, as you can easily pitch it for a fusion, Super Poly cost, etc, meaning it's ROTA effect will go off easily and get your plays starting. ONce in the grave, it can be banished to recur a archetypal S/T back to the board, which is really nice for recovering lost cards on turn 2 to continue plays or manipulating the board state. You can only use one of these effects and once per turn, but it's still powerful. (all of the level 4 or lower Despian's have this hard once per turn, one effect per turn restriction so im only goingt o mention it here for the sake of simplictiy)
3x Comedy- Looking like me after a serious dip in my  mental health, Comedy is a pretty solid card for the deck for protection. It discards itself when a archetypal card you control is targeted for an effect, avoiding various meta cards like Drident. If Comedy is in the grave, it can tribute a fusion to summon itself. It can get fusions in the grave for effects and get bodies on the board, which is nice, but this effect is a bit situational.
3x Albert- God, why did they fucking name it Albert? That sounds so stupid. Anyway, Albert is a solid card, as on summon, it fetches an archetypal S/T. This is really nice, as the archetype uses a lot of S/T and can use the S/T to field swarm and fuse. And, if a face up fusion leaves the field because of the opponent, Albert can special summon himself and Imperm an opponent's monster. Albert's all around really solid as a searcher and control card, aside from the shitty name.
2x Name I can't spell- With a name I can't spell, this monster is really cool but not a staple 3 of, due to it's high level. I play it at 2 since it's a high level, to avoid bricking. Since the deck can search and special a lot, it can still get this monster out easily with it at 2. Anyway, onto the effect: If a monster from the extra is summoned, it can Imperm a monstrer on the board. This effect is amazing for interrupting combos midway through. Additionally, this has a special summoning condition, as if it's sent to the grave or banished for a fusion, you can bring it back. Generally, solid main deck boss monster that can be a bit bricky. The only main flaws is that it's a bit bricky due to a high level and it has a hard once per turn on the Imperm effect.
3x Fallen of Albaz- My baby boy. I included a Albaz engine, because A) lore B) naming shit with some of the cards C) it can easily fuse into some of the Despia monsters with it's effect. It's effect is basically just a super poly on summon, so as long as you have the field set up, you can use it to go into the Despia fusions and clear the opponent's board. Additonally, he can be used for Stigmata of white.
3x Stigmata of White- Stigmata of White is a fusion spell for Albaz, allowing you to use materials from hand, field, and grave, which is amazing and helps a ton with getting multiple fusion bodies on the board. Additionally, if it was discareded for my baby boy, it can be reset to the board, which is amazing.
3x Theatre- Oh god, no. Not the fucking ABYSS ACTOR FLASHBACKS, AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA-
Jeffery Epstien here. I'll be taking over while Amy is having a breakdown. Now what the hell is a yu gi oh card?
The field spell is the main archetypal fusion card, oddly enough. It allows you to fuse any level 8 or higher fusion, not an archetypal one, making this technically generic. This is great and means this archetype has engine potential. Anyway, it uses materials from hand and field, which is pretty standard. Additionally, if a non-fusion Fairy leaves the board because of the opponent, you can special summon a Fusion from your grave, making it hard for the opponent to clear your board. All around amazing card.
3x Curtain Rise- Curtain Rise is a E-tele for the archetype, allowing you to discard one to special summon a Despia from deck. while yes, this does also add a Despia to hand, you're never going to be searching, just summoning, to be honest. Anyway, the discard cost is surprisingly good in this deck, as it triggers Tragedy, a strong card you want in the grave.  Additionally, if a fusion would be destroyed by a card effect, you can banish Curtain Rise from the grave instead. This is also an amazing effect, making it incredibly hard to kill your boss monsters, as a lot of current strong monsters like Big Tiddy Cow rely on popping.
3x Super Poly- Amy decided to include the Super Poly package in this deck, to take full advantage of the generic summoning conditions of the Albaz fusions and the Despian fusions. This helps a lot with wiping boards going second and controlling the board going first. Additionally, it's discard cost triggers Tragedy, and this alongside cards like Albaz and other fusion cards helps to get tons of bodies on board incredibly fast.
2x Poly- Poly is just here in order to generically fuse into the fusions, in cases where your hand may be more bricky or less useful. Poly can also be searched off of Fusion Recycling Plant, which is quite nice.
2x Fusion Recycling Plant- Plant is a pretty nice searcher, as it adds either Poly if you have a clogged up hand, or maybe Super (I am unsure of the rulings of that). Additionally, during the end phase, Recycling Plant can bounce back a used up fusion material from grave to hand, setting up turn 2 plays. Neither of these effects are hard once per turns either.
1x Terraforming- Terraforming has two targets, as if you already have Theatre, you can search Plant, and visa versa. Generally, terra is a versatile and useful card for the deck. It's also Ash bait.
1x One for One- One for One is a solid card for getting bodies on board, as Comedy and Tragedy are both level 1's. Due to this, you can use One for One to help swarm the field for plays. Additionally, One for One discards, meaning it can trigger Tragedy.
3x Judgement- Judgement is a solid card for the deck, as if you control a level 8 or higher fusion (which you should since the archetype centers around them), you can pop the opponent's board of monsters weaker than them. Use this when they're weak, or use this in tandem with Qua, and you have a Raigeki on the opponent's turn for no cost. Fucking solid. It also has the same recursion effect as White.
The solemns- I'll just group them together for simplicity. Since this is control focused, I tossed in 3 Strike and 2 Judgement to halt the opponent's plays. LP doesn't  matter very much and these are solid cards. If you can find the space, I reccomend playing Trap Trick to search them out.
3x Proscsenium- The main boss monster, Proscenium is a big boy with 3200 attack. It also has generic fusion materials, only requiring a Despia and a light and a dark. This makes it a great Super Poly target, as Lights and Darks are the two most common attributes in the game. It's main effect is that, during the MP, it can either banish or steal a extra deck monster from the opponent's graveyard. This is absolutely amazing, as it can interrupt plays, and if you manage to out a powerful boss monster, you can steal it for yourself. Additionally, whenever Prosc destroys a monster by battle, it inflicts damage to the opponent equal to whichever stat of the destroyed montser is higher. This guy is an absolute fucking monster, in both art and effect, and I love him. I like how they didn't resort to just giving it a negate to make it good.
3x Qua- First off, Qua also has great materials, as they're generic. Qua only requires a Despia and a light or Dark, the most common attributes in the game, making it an amazing super poly target. Anyway, Qua allows you to change the attack of all face up monsters, except for level 8 or higher fusions (AKA itself), to 0. This allows you to wipe boards using Judgement, and help you beat over problem monsters. Additionally, since this is a quick effect, it can be a surprisingly good interruption against problem decks like Drytron, which use the attack of the Drytrons for a ritual summon. Additionally, if it leaves the field because of the opponent, it allows you to special summon a Despia or Fallen of Albaz from deck, which is also amazing, and sets up turn 2 plays if your opponent manages to break your board.
2x Brigrand- Brigrand is a great Albaz target, as your opponent will most likely have many higher leveled bodies on board, depending on the match up. You can easily summon Brigrand to wipe their board using Fallen of Albaz. Additionally, only Brigrand can be targeted for effects and it can't be destroyed by battle, making it a strong wall to protect your other monsters.
1x Albion- Albion is also generic, only requiring Albaz and a Light monster. Light is the second most popular attribute in the game, so. Anyway, on summon, albion lets you fusion summon a level 8 or lower fusion, by banishing fusion materials from your graveyard, hand, or field. This effect is amazing, and lets you get multiple bodies on board easily just off of on 1 Albaz.
1x Golden Lord- Super Poly go brrrr. Same goes for the rest of the fusions from here on out
Playing the deck is pretty easy. Going first, you normal Albert, search, fuse into huge fuckin monsters, and set a ton of backrow. Then you just beat the shit out of the opponent and move on with your day. I feel this deck has a ton of potential and is generally pretty powerful as a control deck. Have fun.

deck_excerpt: Just Sera and their Hole (wait what?)
deck_description: Here's the general idea : We don't play generic trap card (e.x. Torrential, Ice prison, Compulse, etc.) because : a) they are unsearchable with traptrix monster, and b) we dont want to fill our GY with trap to keep "Treacherous Trap Hole" alive as long as possible. Because "Treacherous Trap Hole" and "Break Off Trap Hole" is searchable you don't need to run multiple copies of board wipes card, so you could run more handtraps and going second cards which the deck really suffer.   Now, for cards and tech : Main Deck Monster "Traptrix Myrmeleo" is your one card combo, search Treacherous Trap Hole, link to Traptrix Sera and pass. Also its your built in S/T removal. "Traptrix Dionaea" Most of the time you'll use her special summon effect to recycle your Normal Hole card to keep Treacherous Trap Hole alive, but in late game her Normal Summon is also good for free link 2 or xyz monster. "Traptrix Mantis" Bounce back set card, might be a good option to safe your backrow from s/t removal and resetting traps from Traptrix Dionaea so it's not banished. Her normal summon was kinda irrelevant because Traptrix was a normal summon heavy deck. "Traptrix Ginalloa" Extender, might be a good option if your normal summon get interrupted. "Traptrix Nepenthes" You want this to be on field as fast as possible, because additional special summon is always welcome or to add Traptrix Dionaea to hand for follow up. "Traptrix Atrax" Your trap protection, also with Traptrix Mantis on the field, you could basically activate trap the turn it was set. "Traptrix Genlisea" Not included in main deck, but might worth mentioned because Traptrix Utricularia could prevent her set card from banished.   "Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju" & co. is your problem solving cards against non-target and non-destruction by card effect. "Dinowrestler Pankratops" & "Alpha, the Master of Beasts" Big bodies, self explanatory. Also Alpha has interaction with kaiju to bounce it back to your hand.   Spells "Pot of Prosperity"  Most of the time you may only want to banish 3 cards, because most of your win-con was in your extra deck. "Temple of the Kings" Activate traps the turn it was set, allows you to gain advantage even on your first turn. Also give you more offensive ability during your opponent turn. "Harpie's Feather Duster" Your only non-monster s/t removal. You might want to add more from side deck against s/t heavy deck.   Traps "Treacherous Trap Hole" Your main board wipe and most of the time your first Hole card you search. With Temple of the Kings on the field, you could basically destroy up to 4 cards on the field. "Break Off Trap Hole" Your second board wipe option. It's basically your one sided Torrential Tribute that do not destroy your normal Traptrix, though not as effective against link heavy deck. "Traptrix Trap Hole Nightmare" & "Chain Hole" Monster negation, basically. "Floodgate Trap Hole" Flip cards permanently, good option for non-link card. "Gravedigger's Trap Hole" Hit a lot of deck, set this with Temple of the Kings on the field to avoid interrupted during your first turn. "Imperial Order" Best floodgates against spell heavy deck, also protect your s/t from most s/t removal.   Extra Deck Monster "Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder" Board wipe, one of your win-con. "Number S39: Utopia the Lightning" & Utopia Package. 5000 Atk beater, good option against most boss monster. The utopia package is for 4 material Zeus or Lightning. "Evilswarm Exciton Knight" Basically mini Zeus, good board wipe option if you couldn't attack with your xyz. "Traptrix Allomerus" Convert 2 Parallel eXceed into Traptrix monster to make link 1 or link 2, we don't care about her second effect. "Traptrix Rafflesia" Your best defensive option, and also an interuption. "Borrelsword Dragon" Your primary win-con. Could also trigger Break Off Trap Hole to clean up the board for you OTK the opponent. "Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax" Your defensive boss option, protect your girls from being attacked. "I:P Masquerena" Allow you to make Avramax and Borrelsword indestructible by cards effect. "Traptrix Utricularia" You might want to summon her as soon as possible, as she could keep your trap from hitting GY. Also with Temple of the Kings on the field, you could basically activate traps twice. "Traptrix Sera" The main character of Traptrix, Generates advantage for you to grind the enemy.   Basic Combo : Any Traptrix + Parallel eXceed : (Preferably either Nepenthes, Atrax, or Mantis) Normal summon Nepenthes, link Sera, activate Parallel eXceed, xyz to Allomerus, summon back Nepenthes, Sera set Treacherous, link to Utricularia. End phase bring back Nepenthes. Next turn, after you activate Treacherous, flip it back. Nepenthes and Sera SS Mantis and Atrax, Mantis bounce Treacherous back to hand, and now you can activate Treacherous again from hand. Myrmeleo + Temple of the Kings : Normal summon Myrmeleo, search Break Off Trap Hole, activate Temple, set Break Off, Link to Sera, Activate Break Off, Sera SS Dionaea, Set Break Off, Sera set Treacherous. Now you can either SS Utricularia so you could activate Treacherous twice or leave it as it is to have Treacherous + any Hole Sera could search afterward.

deck_excerpt: A Code Talker deck whose major weakness is Nibiru.
deck_description:
P.S.: I plan to use this deck physically. Although I have most of its cards, Accesscode Talker is VERY expensive, hence why I don't run it. Before I explain the strategy, let me tell the history of this deck:
This is my most stable and powerful deck, however, it's a little old, as the last time I really hunkered down to improve it, there were no Nibiru, Zeus or Dragoons around. Thank COVID for that. And, according do MBT, I can upload my decks in here in order to seek advice, so that's what I'm doing. Now, I'm an old-school player that skipped "those wacky black and white cards", and, just as I was getting used to Pendulums (Igknights best deck, let's GOOOOO), Links dropped and made me completely lost. And since I was buying a lot of cards, and VRAINS is a really cool anime, I tried making a Playmaker deck. The first time I managed to make a Decode Talker on a single turn was soooo exciting...... until it got Kaiju'd. Then I found about Cyberse Magician lock, how Cyberse Clock and Quantum Dragons are able to do that lock similarly, how Transcode and Excode Talkers open up zones for them (back when this was a thing, in MR4) and finally, I got to a point where my deck can consistently setup Transcode and Excode protected by Masquerena on turn 1....... Until I got Nibiru'd. So now my deck is trash again, and I really wanna know how to make it playable again.
Okay, now for the ACTUAL strategy: My focus is making a board where most of my monsters are protected, and Excode Talker works wonders for that. The winning formula of this deck consists in having a Transcode Talker on the Extra Monster Zone, pointing to a Excode Talker, that protects it from destruction (and can be revived due to Transcode's effect), plus one of the three locking monsters, either Cyberse Magician, Cyberse Clock Dragon or Cyberse Quantum Dragon on the field, being pointed by the Excode Talker. Any extras are welcome. If everything works and I end up with a Transcode, Excode and one of the three lockers on the field, the locker protects all monsters from attacks or effects, and Excode protects the locker from effects. However, one thing I cannot do is NEGATE, and that is why Nibiru works against me. Since Nibiru does not destroy, neither Excode, Masquerena or the Locker are able to prevent it from working. I THINK (not too sure, though) that Kaiju's, Sphere Mode, Lava Golem and the sort does not work due to the locker disallowing targetting, but since Nibiru neither targets nor destroy.... Let's assume your starting hand contains Clock Wyvern, One-Time Passcode, Cyberse Converter..... and that Nibiru isn't a factor. Normal Summon Clock Wyvern, then Activate its effect to halve its ATK and Special Summon a token. Then, Special Summon Cyberse Converter due to its effect. Activate One-Time Passcode to Special Summon ANOTHER token. Then, you have two options: Bring the Code Talkers to the field, or a Locker. And you can also pick one of two lockers: Cyberse Magician or Cyberse Clock Dragon. I usually assume Code Talkers are better to begin with, but:
Link Summon I:P Masquerena using Clock Wyvern and its Token Link Summon Transcode Talker using I:P Masquerena and Cyberse Converter. This protects Transcode from destruction effects. Activate Transcode's effect and bring back Masquerena from the GY. Link Summon Excode Talker using Masquerena and the remaining Token. That protects Excode from destruction effects, and grants another destruction protection to Transcode, since it points to it. This scenario ends up using 8 summons. So, Nibiru completely breaks it. Using Clock Wyvern's token, Link Summon Link Disciple. Using Passcode's token, Link Summon Link Devotee. This locks our Link-3 summons, sadly. Tribute Devotee using Disciple's effect, draw a card, then return a card to deck. Since Devotee was tributed, Special Summon two Devotee Tokens. Now you gotta decide: Do you want to bring Cyberse Clock Dragon, or Cyberse Magician?
Using Disciple and one Devotee token, Link Summon Cyberse Witch. Link Summon Linkuriboh using the remaining Devotee token. This will trigger Witch's effect, allowing you to tutor Cyberse Magician and Cynet Ritual. Ritual Summon Cyberse Magician using the remaining non-Link Monsters. As long as you have a Link on the field, your opponent can only attack Cyberse Magician (and you have Linkuriboh to protect it once) and can only target Cyberse Magician with effects. Since we summoned 11 monsters, and Nibiru doesn't target, guess what happens? Using Disciple and one Devotee token, Link Summon Clock Spartoi. Activate its effect to tutor Cynet Fusion. Once again, our path branches: Can we attack? If we can, we should boost our Clock Dragon's ATK. Else, we better give it some protection:
Using the remaining token and Cyberse Converter, Link Summon a Link-2 Code Talker. You might go for Inverted, since it can bring one more body to the field. Fusion Summon Cyberse Clock Dragon using Clock Wyvern and one or both of your Link Monsters. Since the idea is a red-like attack, you might go for broke and use both. Activate Clock Dragon's effect and mill 4 for a 4000 ATK Boost. You will enter the Battle Phase having summoned 11 monsters, and probably getting Nibiru'd.... But it's a MIGHTY token.... that will sadly be destroyed soon, since it has pretty much no defense. Using the remaining token, Link Summon Linkuriboh. Fusion Summon Cyberse Clock Dragon, using Clock Wyvern and Clock Spartoi, in the middle zone, or the outermost zone closest to your used Extra. We COULD use Linkuriboh, but we'll need him for some battle protection... If everyone survives (which is VERY unlikely), next turn, using only one summon, we can bring both Transcode and Excode Talkers in a way that also protects our Clock Dragon. However, this uses 11 summons as well.
As you can see, all scenarios lead to Nibiru. We COULD not Special Summon a few monsters on the beginning of the turn, but that would end at most with a unprotected Transcode Talker. So, I need advices. What should I run on this deck?
